docs/discovery_20260329_092950.md:3477:| GW-002 | Create `tools/art_validator.py` implementing programmatic verification loops. After each generation attempt: (1) validate Canvas dimensions match requested size, (2) validate all lines have consistent display width using wcwidth, (3) validate emoji placement doesn't break grid alignment, (4) for AEAF: validate frame count, frame dimensions consistency, and header format, (5) validate output fits within Telegram's 4096-char message limit for text mode. On validation failure, construct a specific error message (e.g., "Line 3 is 22 chars wide, expected 20") and feed it back to the LLM for correction. Maximum 5 retry iterations per generation attempt. | MUST | T2 | - Validator catches width mismatches with specific line numbers<br/>- Validator catches broken emoji alignment<br/>- Validator catches AEAF format errors<br/>- Retry loop fixes issues within 5 iterations >70% of the time<br/>- Telegram char limit enforced<br/>- Each iteration's errors are logged |
docs/discovery_20260329_092950.md:3481:| GW-006 | Create the PostgreSQL art repository schema and data access layer at `tools/art_repository.py`. Tables: `artworks` (id, created_at, art_type, theme, dimensions, palette, pets_featured, canvas_text, aeaf_text, generated_code, png_path, gif_path, thumbnail_path, composite_score, scores_json, qualitative_feedback, generation_model, generation_effort, generation_temperature, assessment_model, generation_time_ms, assessment_time_ms, retry_count, experiment_id, is_favorite, tags), `experiments` (id, created_at, experiment_name, model_id, effort_level, temperature, art_type, dimensions, theme_category, generation_config_json), `model_art_scores` (id, model_id, effort_level, art_type, avg_composite, avg_medium_use, avg_visual_appeal, avg_expressiveness, avg_creativity, avg_precision, sample_count, last_updated). Use psycopg2 with connection pooling. | MUST | T2 | - All tables created in cypherclaw_observatory PostgreSQL database<br/>- CRUD operations work for artworks, experiments, model_art_scores<br/>- Connection pooling with max 5 connections<br/>- Artwork insert returns generated ID<br/>- Query by model, score range, art_type, date range all work<br/>- model_art_scores auto-updated on new assessment |
docs/discovery_20260329_092950.md:3484:| GW-009 | Integrate art generation into the daemon's 30-minute scheduler. Every 30 minutes (offset from health checks): (1) select art parameters — theme based on system state 50% of the time (server load, pet moods, active tasks, time of day) and pure creative exploration 50% of the time, (2) select model configuration — during calibration, pick the next untested config from the experiment grid; after calibration, use the optimal config with 20% exploration of other configs, (3) generate artwork via art engine, (4) assess via art assessor, (5) store in repository, (6) display in Telegram — send text version in code block + rendered PNG as photo, (7) log everything to Observatory. The art display should accompany (not replace) the health check when they coincide. | MUST | T2 | - Art generated every 30 minutes automatically<br/>- Theme selection alternates between reactive and creative<br/>- During calibration: systematic config testing<br/>- After calibration: optimal config with 20% exploration<br/>- Text version sent as Telegram code block<br/>- PNG sent as Telegram photo<br/>- Observatory event logged with all metadata<br/>- Health check and art display coexist when scheduled together |
docs/discovery_20260329_092950.md:3485:| GW-010 | Implement pet-scene generation. Every artwork must feature one or more of CypherClaw's Tamagotchi pets. Scene modes: (a) **Artist attribution** — the pet whose model generated the piece is shown creating/presenting it, (b) **State reflection** — pet's current Tamagotchi state (mood, energy, hunger, stage) determines the scene (tired pet napping, happy pet playing, hungry pet searching for food), (c) **Multi-pet interaction** — collaborative scenes with 2+ pets (teaching, playing, competing, exploring together). The scene mode is varied across generations, with equal probability for each mode. Pet portraits from `pet_sprites.py` should be composited into the Canvas using the DSL's `composite()` method. | MUST | T2 | - Each artwork features at least one pet<br/>- Artist attribution mode: generating model's pet shown<br/>- State reflection mode: current Tamagotchi stats drive scene<br/>- Multi-pet interaction mode: 2+ pets in scene<br/>- Modes distributed roughly equally over time<br/>- Pet sprites from pet_sprites.py used via Canvas.composite()<br/>- Pet stage (Egg through Master) reflected in portrait used |
docs/discovery_20260329_092950.md:3486:| GW-011 | Implement Tamagotchi-style animations for Telegram. Animated pieces should be short (3-5 frames), loop-friendly, and evoke the feel of a virtual pet game. Frame transitions should show pet movement, expression changes, or environmental shifts. Use the existing AEAF player (`tools/glyphweave/player.py`) for Telegram message-edit playback at 3000ms minimum frame interval. Also render as animated GIF for the gallery. Animation themes: pet idle animations, pet reactions to events (task complete, evolution, feeding), weather/time-of-day cycles, mini-scenes (pet cooking, coding, stargazing). | SHOULD | T2 | - Animations are 3-5 frames long<br/>- Frame interval >= 3000ms (Telegram rate limit)<br/>- AEAF player used for Telegram display<br/>- Animated GIF generated for gallery<br/>- Pet expression/position changes between frames<br/>- At least 5 distinct animation themes implemented<br/>- Animations feel cohesive (smooth transitions, no jarring jumps) |
docs/discovery_20260329_092950.md:3500:Install dependencies, copy reference docs, create sandbox, create PostgreSQL schema. No LLM calls yet — pure infrastructure.
docs/discovery_20260329_092950.md:3503:Build the art engine, validator, prompt templates, and PNG renderer. This is the core creation pipeline. Test with manual invocation.
docs/discovery_20260329_092950.md:3519:**GlyphWeave sits at a crossroads of traditions spanning millennia — from Mesopotamian mosaic tesserae to BBS-era ANSI art packs to modern emoji copypasta on Discord.** This research identifies the aesthetic precedents, technical constraints, LLM generation strategies, and community contexts that should inform its specification. The central finding across all four research areas is that constraint-based modular composition is the unifying thread: every successful text art tradition thrives on a defined grid, a limited vocabulary, and community-driven exchange. GlyphWeave's hybrid ASCII + emoji approach would bridge two currently separate worlds — the CP437 tradition of the ANSI artscene and modern Unicode/emoji culture — a gap no existing format or tool explicitly fills.
docs/discovery_20260329_092950.md:3527:The modern text art tradition begins with Victorian typographical mosaics and early typewriter art, but its aesthetic maturity arrived with BBS culture in the 1980s–90s. **ACiD Productions**, founded in September 1990 by five members, grew to 700+ artists and released 152 artpacks, establishing the artpack — a curated collection of individual works distributed through BBS networks — as the dominant distribution model. Their rival **iCE Advertisements** (founded 1991 in Canada) and successors like **Blocktronics** (founded 2008) sustained this tradition. The scene peaked in 1997 with over 800 artpacks released across all groups. Artists worked within 79-column terminals using IBM Code Page 437's 256 glyphs and ANSI escape sequences providing 16 foreground and 8 background colors.
docs/discovery_20260329_092950.md:3555:- **Programmatic verification loops**: Self-Refine (Madaan et al., NeurIPS 2023) demonstrated ~20% improvement through Generate → Feedback → Refine cycles. For GlyphWeave, a validator can check line widths, character positions, and emoji placement, feeding precise error messages ("Line 3 is 22 chars wide, expected 20") back to the model. Research suggests diminishing returns after **3–5 iterations**.
docs/discovery_20260329_092950.md:3581:The text art ecosystem in 2025 is bifurcated but thriving. The traditional artscene maintains active groups — **Mistigris** (founded 1994, 14,348 lifetime artworks, 8 releases in 2024 and 8 in 2025) and **Blocktronics** continue releasing packs archived at **16colo.rs**, the primary online archive with self-upload capability. Demoparties with dedicated textmode competition categories include **TMDC** (now in its 20th edition at tmdc.scene.org), **Deadline** (Germany), **Flashparty** (Argentina, with separate categories for ANSI, Amiga ASCII, PC ASCII, PETSCII, and teletext art), and **Revision** (the largest demoparty). Anders Carlsson's TEXT-MODE Tumblr (text-mode.tumblr.com / text-mode.org) curates text graphics "going back thousands of years."
docs/discovery_20260329_092950.md:3589:Community attitudes toward AI are divided. The traditional artscene values handcraft — demoparty competitions typically require original human creation, and Revision 2025 hosted a seminar "AI vs Law, Round 1." But the broader casual ecosystem shows no resistance, with tools like Skywork AI's ASCII Text Generator (launched globally May 2025) and Bejamas's AI ASCII Art Generator gaining adoption. ASCIIBench (December 2024) positions ASCII art as a "stress test for multimodal representations," while ArtPerception (October 2025) demonstrates that LLMs have a paradoxical dual relationship with text art — they can interpret visual patterns in ASCII art (enabling jailbreaks) while struggling to generate it spatially.
docs/discovery_20260329_092950.md:3595:Eight principles emerge from this cross-domain investigation. First, **constraint is generative** — every successful text art tradition thrives on defined limits, and GlyphWeave should embrace a specified character vocabulary and grid system as creative enablers. Second, **two-phase LLM generation is essential** — free reasoning followed by constrained output, leveraging VoT-style intermediate visualization. Third, **modular composition over freeform generation** — LLMs are far more reliable assembling pre-defined blocks than generating arbitrary spatial arrangements, aligning with the tile/tessera/artpack traditions. Fourth, **image export is non-negotiable** — the emoji width problem across terminals, browsers, and chat clients makes pixel-perfect rendering impossible without a rasterization layer. Fifth, **the cell model must be grapheme-cluster-native**, storing EGC strings with explicit display widths rather than raw code points. Sixth, **asciicast v2 is the right animation foundation**, extensible via custom event types while inheriting streaming, crash safety, and ecosystem compatibility. Seventh, **the gap GlyphWeave fills is real** — no existing tool or format bridges CP437-tradition text art with modern Unicode/emoji, and both communities are active and growing. Eighth, **small grids win** — keeping compositions under ~15×15 cells aligns with LLM reliability limits, the pixel art tradition of implied detail, and the kaomoji tradition's expressive power within minimal space.```
